
This is a new project. The goal is to test "conformance" of a large number of
open source graphql implementations. The way this works is that we will have a
corpus of graphql inputs, describing a schema and a sequence of queries and variables that can be executed against that schema.

For example:
./conformer/corpus/1                    # test-1
./conformer/corpus/1/schema.graphqls    # the schema for test-1
./conformer/corpus/1/query-1.graphql    # query-1 for test-1
./conformer/corpus/1/variables-1.json   # variables-1 for test-1
./conformer/corpus/1/query-2.graphql    # query-2 for test-1
./conformer/corpus/1/variables-2.json   # variables-2 for test-1

This project features a coordinating component written in nodejs that lives under conformer/src. 
This component is responsible for reading conformer/config.json, which is a configuration file in the format of:
  {
    reference: {
      path: "./impls/graphql-js"
    },
    conformants: [
      { path: "./impls/hot-chocolate" },
      { path: "./impls/gqlgen" },
      { path: "./impls/graphql-java" },
    ]
  }

The reads this configuration file, and then executes a nodejs "conformer-harness.js" test harness
at the path of each reference and conformants object.

Each conformer-harness.js reads inputs from stdin, in the order of:
<absolute-path-to-schema-file> <absolute-path-to-query-file>
<absolute-path-to-variables-file> It then starts a simple implementation of the
graphql implementation using the standard idioms of that language. For example,
in graphql-java, the harness will invoke a main class that reads the schema at
the provided file path, and wires it up using the Wiring Spec described below.
Then it will execute the requested document with the requested variables, and
print the graphql result to stdout.

The conformer-harness receives the graphql result from the implementation, and
passes it back to the coordinator.

The coordinator compares the response from each conformant impl against the
response from the reference impl

## Wiring Spec
Each implementation will wire it's schema such that:
- every Int value is 2
- every Float value is 3.14
- every String value is "str"
- every Boolean value is true
- every nullable field is returned as non-null
- every union is resolved as the alphabetically first member type
- every interface is resolved as the alphabetically last implementing type
- every list field returns 2 values
- every enum field returns its first value

